            <h3>What are the health implications of BMI?</h3>
            <p>BMI is a useful indicator of body fatness for most people. However, it does not directly measure body fat. For a comprehensive understanding, consult the CDC's guidelines on BMI and health risks <a href="https://www.cdc.gov/bmi/index.html">(CDC)</a>.</p>
            <h3>What is the role of BMI in health assessments?</h3>
            <p>BMI is often used in health assessments to categorize individuals into weight categories that may lead to health problems. For more information, see the National Heart, Lung, and Blood Institute's resources on BMI <a href="https://www.nhlbi.nih.gov/health/heart-healthy-living/healthy-weight#:~:text=A%20healthy%20weight%20for%20adults,are%20at%20a%20healthy%20weight.">(NHLBI, 2022)</a>.</p>
            <p>The Craving Index is a measure used to evaluate an individual's craving levels for certain foods. It helps in understanding eating behaviors and can be a useful tool in weight management strategies.</p>
			<p>Pelchat, Marcia L. "Of human bondage: food craving, obsession, compulsion, and addiction." Physiology & behavior 76, no. 3 (2002): 347-352. <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/0803672">https://www.nature.com/articles/0803672</a></p>
            <h3>What is BMI?</h3>
            <p>Body Mass Index (BMI) is a widely used metric to assess whether a person has a healthy body weight for a given height. It is calculated by dividing a person's weight in kilograms by the square of their height in meters. For further reading, refer to the World Health Organization's guidelines on BMI <a href="https://www.who.int/news-room/fact-sheets/detail/obesity-and-overweight">(WHO, 2021)</a>.</p>
